article.description: The Sting can take one positive from their three-game losing streak: It hasn't hurt them in the tight Eastern Conference race.
article.headline: Sting, Liberty tied for second in East
article.linkText: Sting lose twice: NY wins, Fever stay in first
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The Charlotte Sting can take one positive
from their three-game losing streak: It hasn't hurt them in the
tight Eastern Conference race.

The Sting missed a chance to tie first-place Indiana on Tuesday
when the New York Liberty beat them 80-74 in overtime.

"That's basically how crazy the East is, we can lose three in a
row and still be in it," said guard Dawn Staley. "We know what it
will take to finish out good, we just have to do it."

With the victory -- New York's second win over Charlotte in three
days -- the Liberty pulled into a three-way tie with the Sting and
Connecticut for second place in the East.

"We knew we had to take care of business and we did a good
job," said Becky Hammon, who had 17 points and 10 assists for New
York.

New York was coming off a 75-58 victory over Charlotte, the
Sting's most lopsided defeat in almost two years. This one wasn't
as easy, but it gave the Liberty a 3-0 season sweep.

New York led by as many as seven in the game and clung to a
70-66 lead with 27 seconds to play in regulation.

But Charlotte rallied with a driving layup by Allison Feaster
and a putback by Olympia Scott-Richardson to tie it with 19 seconds
left.

"Charlotte has too much pride and too much experience to give
up and give you the game," said New York interim coach Pat Coyle.
"We let them get back in the game."

Both teams had a chance to win it, but Crystal Robinson missed a
3 for New York and Staley missed for Charlotte.

The Liberty then took over in the extra period.

Bethany Donaphin opened overtime with a jumper before Vickie
Johnson hit a 3 to put the Liberty up 75-70. Hammon then scored
four consecutive points on a layup and a pair of free throws to
seal the win.

The Sting nearly went scoreless in overtime, missing four shots
and turning it over four times before Feaster hit a jumper with 21
seconds to play.

Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey was critical of the Sting following
the loss.

"What I am most disappointed in is our team effort," she said.
"We don't play all the time with effort. There's no consistency in
rebounding, boxing out, defense and running the floor."

All five of New York's starters were in double figures. Donaphin
scored 14, Elena Baranova had 12 points and 12 rebounds, and
Robinson and Johnson added 10 points.

Staley led Charlotte with 19 points, Olympia Scott-Richardson
scored a season-high 16, Tynesha Lewis had 13 and Feaster added 11.
